1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 {The most popular move against Trompowsky attack. Black
aims to attack our bishop on g5 and to gain a tempo. Simple as that. We are
going to start with the sharpest Variation against Ne4. That is Raptor
Variation!} 3. h4 $5 {White does several things with this move.. 1. White
prevents e6 move. As you see, e6 is something that black has to do soon or
later. 2. In the case of Nxg5, h-file will be opened, which is good for white,
cause, white can attack black kingside castle via h-file and white h1-rook is
a powerful piece 3. In the case of h6, white can simply pull back his bishop
to f4. After that, short castle is suspicious move for black, because he
already weakened his kingside. White can simply play g4, g5 with strong attack
There are two main moves for black: c5 or d5. Let's check c5 first} c5 {The
main move. Black is looking for the counterplay on the queenside. Black is
trying to play Qb6 or Qa5, because our dark square bishop is already out and
b2 pawn is no longer defended} 4. dxc5 {We don't want to allow Qb6, so we take
on c5. The thing is that black should focus on taking back c5-pawn. He has two
good moves: Qa5 and Na6. Other moves are not so good} Qa5+ {The main move} (
4... Na6 {This is something that black can also do.. He wants to take on c5
with his a-Knight and to keep e4- Knight in the center} 5. Nd2 Naxc5 6. Nxe4
Nxe4 7. Qd5 {We centralize our queen! Knight on e4 is hanging, so black has 2
options: to take on g5 or to play Nf6} Nf6 (7... Nxg5 {More solid move than
Nf6, but, he opens h-file for our rook} 8. hxg5 Qb6 {This is the main move.
Black attacks b2 and f2 pawns} 9. O-O-O {Just keep developing pieces!} Qxf2 {
It looks tempting to take on f2, but the problem for black is that he
developed only his queen so far. On the onther hand white's major pieces are
well placed. We need to develop minor pieces and after that we will have
better position} 10. Kb1 {Prophylactic move! We simply move our king on safe
place and we avoid checks} e6 11. Qd3 Qc5 12. Nf3 g6 (12... d5 $2 13. e4 $1 $16
) (12... d6 $2 13. g6 fxg6 14. Rxh7 $16) 13. Nd2 Be7 14. Ne4 Qe5 15. Nf6+ Bxf6
16. gxf6 Qxf6 17. g4 $1 $13 {White sacrificed two pawns for initiative! Black
king is still in the center and he can not move him. Also, c8-bishop is very
bad and it doesn't have bright future In my opinion, it's much better position
for white, although computer says that it's equal. The thing is that for human,
this position is very difficult and demanding. It's almost impossible to find
a good plan and to develop pieces, at least}) 8. Bxf6 exf6 {Huge mistake.. d7
pawn is weak and isolated forever} (8... gxf6 9. O-O-O d6 10. e3 a6 11. Ne2 {
Interesting move.. Try to remember it. We want to jump on g3 where the Knight
can reach h5 or f5 square} Qc7 12. Kb1 Bd7 13. Nf4 (13. Ng3 Rc8 14. Bd3 $14 {
Black has a problem with his development.. His bishop on f8 is the biggest
problem. Also, his king isn't so great in the center})) 9. O-O-O Be7 10. e3 O-O
11. Nf3 d6 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Bd3 $16 {And white has much better play}) (4... Nc6
{Black continue to develop pieces.. Nc6 is a solid move. Again, we do the same}
5. Nd2 Nxc5 6. e4 d6 (6... d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Ngf3 Bf5 9. Bc4 Qd6 {Now, we
can't play Qe2 and 0-0-0, because of Bxc2. Instead, 0-0 is good enough} 10. O-O
h6 11. Be3 e6 12. Bb5 $14 {With Nc4 idea.. White is slightly better}) 7. Ngf3
h6 8. Be3 Bg4 9. c3 e6 10. Be2 Be7 11. Nd4 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Ne5 13. O-O-O O-O 14.
Kb1 {Interesting position. White aims to play g4 and to organize attack on
black kingside}) 5. Nd2 Nxd2 (5... Nxg5 {The main move} 6. hxg5 {There are two
possible moves for black: g6 or Qxc5} g6 (6... Qxc5 7. g6 {The most aggressive
move! Black has to take. Otherwise, white is going to play gxf7 and black king
will be on a dangerous place} fxg6 {1. White has opened h-file 2. Black has a
few weaknesses: g6-pawn and f7-squer. Generally speaking, light squares are
weak. b1-h7 and a2-g8 diagonals are our best option for an attack. And of
course, h-file} 8. e3 {We want to develop light bishop as soon as possible} Nc6
{Ngf3 is the best move.. Bd3 looks like a natural move, but the problem is Nb4
and we need to move bishop from good diagonal} 9. Ngf3 $1 (9. Bd3 $6 Nb4 10.
Bxg6+ hxg6 11. Rxh8 Nxc2+ 12. Kf1 Nxa1 13. Qxa1 b6 {and black has better
position...}) 9... d6 10. Nb3 Qb6 (10... Qf5 {Better move than Qb6. Black
keeps his queen on the kingside} 11. Nbd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qa5+ (12... Qf7 $2 13.
Bb5+ $16) (12... Qc5 13. Bd3 Qg5 14. Nf3 Qf6 15. c3 e6 16. Nh4 Rg8 17. Qb3 Be7
18. Nf3 Rh8 19. O-O-O $16 {Black pieces are tied up.. White has much better
pieces and safe king. Also, h-file is opened for potential attack on black
king. Black can't develop his light bishop because of Qxb7}) (12... Qg5 13. c3
e6 (13... e5 $2 14. Nb5 Qd8 15. Qd5 a6 16. O-O-O axb5 17. Bxb5+ Bd7 18. Qe6+
Qe7 19. Bxd7+ $14) 14. Qb3 d5 15. Bb5+ Kf7 16. O-O-O $16) 13. c3 e5 14. Nf3 Be6
15. Ng5 Bg8 16. Bd3 O-O-O 17. Bxg6 Be7 18. Nf7 Bxf7 19. Bxf7 $14) 11. Bd3 {
Black has a big problem.. g6 pawn is hangin and the only good move is Bf5} Bf5
12. Ng5 Bxd3 13. Qxd3) 7. c3 {Important move. White is threatening to play b4,
so black has to take on c5} Qxc5 8. Ne4 $5 Qe5 (8... Qb6 9. e3 $1 {Black can't
take on b2. That's too risky and dangerous} Qxb2 $6 (9... Nc6 10. Bc4 Bg7 11.
Ne2 d6 12. Qb3 {Good move. After Qxb3, a-file will be opened for white's rook.
Endgame will be much better for white, because a7 and h7 pawns are constantly
under attack} Qxb3 13. axb3 $14) 10. Bc4 Bg7 11. Rb1 Qa3 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Ne2
$40 {All white pieces are well placed. White is going to play king to f1 and
to organize attack on black king via h-file}) 9. Rh4 $1 {We are going to gain
a tempo with Nf3. This is unusual and sharp position} Bg7 10. Nf3 Qc7 11. e3 d6
12. Bc4 Nc6 13. Qe2 Bd7 (13... O-O 14. O-O-O $16 {Our next move is Rdh1 and
black has huge problems}) (13... Bf5 14. O-O-O Rc8 15. Bd5 Kf8 16. g4 Bxe4 17.
Bxe4 e6 18. Kb1 $14 {Sharp position.. White is better again, because of opened
h-file and more active pieces}) 14. O-O-O Na5 15. Bd5 {If black moves his
e-pawn at any moment, he will make a hole on f6. Also, d6 pawn will be weak}
O-O-O 16. Bxf7 {White took a pawn, which means that white is better.. Also,
white pieces are more active} Kb8 17. Bd5 $16) 6. Qxd2 Qxd2+ $2 {This is a
mistake.. Now, white can successfully protect c5- pawn} (6... Qxc5 {Definitely
better move than Qxd2} 7. e4 {With this move, white gains the space in the
center and prevents d5} Nc6 8. O-O-O d6 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. Be3 Qa5 (10... Qh5 $2 {
Queen is doing nothing on h5 and it's impossible mission for him to develop
other pieces, for example his f8-bishop} 11. Be2 g6 (11... e6 12. Qc3 {After
Qc3, the only move for black is Qa5 again, but after that, it's almost the
same position like before} Qa5 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. h5 $14) 12. Qc3 Rg8 13. Rd5 g5
14. Rb5 $18) 11. Qxa5 Nxa5 12. h5 $1 {Our idea is to play Rh4. It's very
unpleasant move for black, because, he doesn't have appropriate square for his
bishop. Also, we want to create presure on black kingside and to push h-pawn
to h6 in a good moment} h6 (12... e5 {Probably the best move for black.
However, black is facing with new weakness- pawn on d6} 13. Bb5+ Nc6 14. Rh4
Be6 15. Ng5 Bd7 16. Bc4 Nd8 17. f4 $16 {Pressure in the center is huge! White
has well placed and coordinated pieces. On the other hand, black king is still
in the center and his pieces are not so great}) 13. Rh4 Bd7 14. e5 $16) 7. Bxd2
e6 8. b4 a5 9. c3 $14 {White should develop his pieces from the kingside and
he has better position because of the extra pawn} *

